                          <p id="fs-idp27984704">
                            <span data-type="title">Check Your Learning</span>
                            Silver crystallizes in an FCC structure. The edge length of its unit cell is 409 pm.
                          </p>
                          <p
                            id="fs-idp63739072"
                          >(a) What is the atomic radius of Ag in this structure?</p>
                          <p
                            id="fs-idp100438656"
                          >(b) Calculate the density of Ag.</p>
                          <div data-type="note" id="fs-idp137915824">
                            <h3 class="os-title" data-type="title">
                              <span
                                class="os-title-label"
                                data-type
                                id="[redacted for uniqueness]"
                              >Answer:</span>
                            </h3>
                            <div class="os-note-body">
                              <p id="fs-idm27761408">
                                (a) 144 pm; (b) 10.5 g/cm
                                <sup>3</sup>
                              </p>
                            </div>
                          </div>
                        </div>
                        <p id="fs-idp26628704">
                          In general, a unit cell is defined by the lengths of three axes (
                          <em data-effect="italics">a</em>,
                          <em data-effect="italics">b</em>, and
                          <em data-effect="italics">c</em>) and the angles (
                          <em data-effect="italics">α</em>,
                          <em data-effect="italics">β</em>, and
                          <em data-effect="italics">γ</em>) between them, as illustrated in
                          <a
                            class="autogenerated-content"
                            href="#CNX_Chem_10_06_GenUnitCll"
                          >Figure 10.55</a>. The axes are defined as being the lengths between points in the space lattice. Consequently, unit cell axes join points with identical environments.
                        </p>
                        <div class="os-figure" id="CNX_Chem_10_06_GenUnitCll">
                          <figure
                            class="scaled-down"
                            data-id="CNX_Chem_10_06_GenUnitCll"
                          >
                            <span
                              data-alt="A cube is shown where each corner has a black dot drawn on it. A circle in the bottom of the cube is composed of three double-ended arrows. The left top of this circle is labeled “alpha,” the top right is labeled “beta” and the bottom is labeled “gamma.” The bottom left corner of the cube is labeled “a” while the bottom of the back face is labeled “b” and the top, back, left corner is labeled “c.”"
                              data-type="media"
                              id="fs-idm117541936"
                            >
                              <img
                                alt="A cube is shown where each corner has a black dot drawn on it. A circle in the bottom of the cube is composed of three double-ended arrows. The left top of this circle is labeled “alpha,” the top right is labeled “beta” and the bottom is labeled “gamma.” The bottom left corner of the cube is labeled “a” while the bottom of the back face is labeled “b” and the top, back, left corner is labeled “c.”"
                                data-media-type="image/jpeg"
                                id="[redacted for uniqueness]"
                                src="/resources/e50e9dde1f9868004f84d87e98a2fa539bba3fc7"
                              >
                            </span>
                          </figure>
                          <div class="os-caption-container">
                            <span class="os-title-label">Figure</span>
                            <span class="os-number">10.55</span>
                            <span class="os-divider"></span>
                            <span class="os-divider"></span>
                            <span class="os-caption">
                              A unit cell is defined by the lengths of its three axes (
                              <em data-effect="italics">a</em>,
                              <em data-effect="italics">b</em>, and
                              <em data-effect="italics">c</em>) and the angles (
                              <em data-effect="italics">α</em>,
                              <em data-effect="italics">β</em>, and
                              <em data-effect="italics">γ</em>) between the axes.
                            </span>
                          </div>
                        </div>
                        <p id="fs-idm92224">
                          There are seven different lattice systems, some of which have more than one type of lattice, for a total of fourteen different unit cells, which have the shapes shown in
                          <a
                            class="autogenerated-content"
                            href="#CNX_Chem_10_06_CrystalSys"
                          >Figure 10.56</a>.
                        </p>
                        <div class="os-figure" id="CNX_Chem_10_06_CrystalSys">
